00:23:28,423 --> 00:23:32,018
...if we don't go after that ship,
it's gonna haunt us the rest of our lives.

258
00:23:32,194 --> 00:23:34,526
I wasted eight years of my life
on this bullshit.

259
00:23:34,696 --> 00:23:37,358
I'm going back to Chicago.
I'm gonna get my Ph. D...

260
00:23:37,532 --> 00:23:41,332
...and I'm going to spend the rest of my life
teaching, reading and writing books.

261
00:23:41,503 --> 00:23:44,768
And somewhere in there I'm gonna meet
an intelligent, successful man...

262
00:23:44,940 --> 00:23:49,877
...who can get through an entire
conversation without using "definitely. "

263
00:23:51,813 --> 00:23:55,874
First of all,
I hardly ever say that anymore.

264
00:23:56,451 --> 00:24:00,410
And when are you gonna stop selling
this crap about going back to school?

265
00:24:00,589 --> 00:24:03,922
You want history?
It's under the ocean, lady.

266
00:24:05,127 --> 00:24:08,392
What, are you telling me you wanna
spend your life in some dark room...

267
00:24:08,563 --> 00:24:10,963
...taking notes and writing books...

268
00:24:11,133 --> 00:24:14,296
...about what some old putz in
another room cooked up in his head...

269
00:24:14,469 --> 00:24:16,903
...about things
that you have actually seen...

270
00:24:17,072 --> 00:24:20,838
...and touched and pulled out of the sand
with your own hands?

271
00:24:23,945 --> 00:24:25,742
Bullshit.

272
00:24:28,283 --> 00:24:30,979
I'm so glad we're not married anymore.

273
00:24:37,159 --> 00:24:40,492
Well, where are you gonna get
the tuition money anyway?

274
00:24:40,662 --> 00:24:43,825
That's the best part. By selling the boat.

275
00:24:44,799 --> 00:24:48,064
By selling my boat, which belongs to me,
which used to belong to us...

276
00:24:48,236 --> 00:24:50,704
...but you missed the divorce
so now it belongs to me.

277
00:24:51,273 --> 00:24:54,333
I'm gonna fix it up, I'm gonna sell it,
and I'm going back... What?

278
00:24:54,509 --> 00:24:55,635
This is hard to say.

279
00:24:55,810 --> 00:24:57,437
What is?

280
00:25:15,397 --> 00:25:17,922
Well, you act like this is totally my fault.

281
00:25:18,867 --> 00:25:21,597
Can I borrow this cane
for a second, please?

282
00:25:21,770 --> 00:25:23,499
Oh, come on, Tess.
You're not gonna hit me.

283
00:25:23,672 --> 00:25:24,934
Ugh.

284
00:25:28,743 --> 00:25:30,370
Sorry.

285
00:26:02,644 --> 00:26:04,509
Oh, my God.

286
00:26:06,214 --> 00:26:07,875
Oh, my God.

287
00:26:09,117 --> 00:26:10,516
Oh, God.

288
00:26:39,080 --> 00:26:41,605
I take it they didn't kill you.

289
00:26:45,620 --> 00:26:46,985
No...

290
00:26:47,555 --> 00:26:49,284
...but thanks for your help.

291
00:26:49,924 --> 00:26:52,324
- You need help.
- You are not my mother.

292
00:26:52,494 --> 00:26:53,518
You're right.

293
00:26:53,695 --> 00:26:57,131
I guess maybe I act like your mother
sometimes because I never had one.

294
00:26:57,299 --> 00:26:58,357
Easy, Gary, easy.

295
00:26:58,533 --> 00:27:01,468
Okay, look, the main thing is
we get away from Key West.

296
00:27:01,636 --> 00:27:05,470
The second Finn lays eyes on this boat,
he's gonna be onboard in 10 minutes.

297
00:27:05,640 --> 00:27:08,074
What do you mean?
You told him you're working here?

298
00:27:08,243 --> 00:27:10,473
- Are you kidding?
- Then I don't get it.

299
00:27:11,046 --> 00:27:13,139
He needs money, Gary.

300
00:27:13,348 --> 00:27:16,283
Another boat, new equipment, everything.

301
00:27:16,451 --> 00:27:19,682
And I doubt he's gonna squeeze
another dime out of that Bugs Bunny.

302
00:27:19,854 --> 00:27:23,051
- Bugs Bunny?
- The rapper guy we had the fight about.

303
00:27:23,224 --> 00:27:25,021
- You mean Bigg Bunny Deenz?
- Yeah.

304
00:27:25,193 --> 00:27:27,991
- Bigg Bunny Deenz is Finn's investor?
- Yeah.

305
00:27:28,163 --> 00:27:31,257
- Hey, Gary?
- He is a very dangerous guy.

306
00:27:31,433 --> 00:27:33,799
I did like that one song he had,
"Call Me Thumper. "

307
00:27:33,968 --> 00:27:35,162
That was some funny shit.

308
00:27:35,337 --> 00:27:37,635
- Anyway...
- There's something wrong with my bisque.

309
00:27:37,806 --> 00:27:39,205
- I'm sorry, honey.
- Anyway...

310
00:27:39,374 --> 00:27:42,104
But I don't get it,
because has Finn ever even met Nigel?

311
00:27:42,277 --> 00:27:44,939
No. But he will, don't you understand?

312
00:27:45,113 --> 00:27:47,809
He is a genius at exactly three things:

313
00:27:47,982 --> 00:27:53,420
Treasure salving, finding money
for treasure salving, and one other thing.

314
00:27:55,390 --> 00:27:57,324
- What other thing?
- What other thing?

315
00:27:59,060 --> 00:28:00,721
I don't wanna talk about it.

316
00:28:00,895 --> 00:28:03,022
How do you plan to get another boat?

317
00:28:03,198 --> 00:28:06,463
I can't think about this right now, Alfonz.

318
00:28:07,635 --> 00:28:09,068
I just got divorced.

319
00:28:10,238 --> 00:28:12,433
May I make a suggestion?

320
00:28:13,575 --> 00:28:14,974
No.

321
00:28:16,411 --> 00:28:18,709
You see that big yacht lying offshore?

322
00:28:19,347 --> 00:28:20,371
No, which one?

323
00:28:20,548 --> 00:28:23,381
The owner is Nigel Honeycutt.

324
00:28:24,686 --> 00:28:26,278
- So what?
- I only mention it...

325
00:28:26,454 --> 00:28:31,790
...because he is worth $ 700 million.

326
00:28:33,928 --> 00:28:37,625
And just to let you know,
I'm back onboard, obviously.

327
00:28:38,032 --> 00:28:40,592
So whenever you want to weigh anchor
is great.

328
00:28:41,369 --> 00:28:42,836
Thank you.

329
00:28:43,505 --> 00:28:45,370
So should I tell the captain?

330
00:28:45,540 --> 00:28:47,667
Ready to weigh anchor?
Ready to push off?

331
00:28:48,777 --> 00:28:50,506
Actually, no.

332
00:28:50,678 --> 00:28:53,806
My daughter, Gemma, is joining us today...

333
00:28:53,982 --> 00:28:55,973
...and I said I would wait here for her.

334
00:28:56,151 --> 00:28:58,619
Oh, great. God.

335
00:28:59,521 --> 00:29:01,614
When is she coming?
Where is she coming from?

336
00:29:01,790 --> 00:29:03,815
How far away is she? How great.

337
00:29:04,225 --> 00:29:06,386
I sent the chopper to Miami...

338
00:29:07,028 --> 00:29:09,496
...but she could be anywhere.

339
00:29:09,664 --> 00:29:13,156
That's so funny that you would wait
in Key West for her...

340
00:29:13,334 --> 00:29:16,064
...when she's coming by chopper.

341
00:29:16,237 --> 00:29:18,296
- Is it?
- Well, just because the helicopter...

342
00:29:18,473 --> 00:29:20,202
...could just meet the boat anywhere.

343
00:29:20,375 --> 00:29:24,607
I mean, anywhere at all, that's what's
so incredibly great about helicopters.

344
00:29:25,613 --> 00:29:28,138
She wants to do some shopping.

345
00:29:34,956 --> 00:29:36,446
What do you do, Tess?

346
00:29:38,626 --> 00:29:41,026
I'm the new steward.

347
00:29:42,230 --> 00:29:44,027
But what do you really do?

348
00:29:44,199 --> 00:29:48,465
What makes you think I do anything
besides stewarding?

349
00:29:48,636 --> 00:29:52,834
Stewing, stewarding,
stewarding? Stewarding.

350
00:29:53,007 --> 00:29:57,706
My infallible lifelong instinct
for sizing people up.

351
00:30:00,448 --> 00:30:01,813
Have you sized me up?

352
00:30:02,984 --> 00:30:04,576
Not quite.

353
00:30:06,154 --> 00:30:10,318
You don't mind the work,
but you're not here for long.

354
00:30:10,825 --> 00:30:15,990
You have a deep but not entirely unclouded
love for the sea.

355
00:30:16,998 --> 00:30:20,126
You perform your duties
with superlative efficiency and ease...

356
00:30:20,301 --> 00:30:23,099
...suggestive of someone expending
approximately one-tenth...

357
00:30:23,271 --> 00:30:25,136
...of her available brain power.

358
00:30:26,441 --> 00:30:27,874
So...

359
00:30:28,676 --> 00:30:31,440
...what do you do
with the remaining 90 percent...

360
00:30:31,613 --> 00:30:33,547
...when you're not getting divorced?

361
00:30:37,151 --> 00:30:39,381
I hope I'm not being too personal.

362
00:30:42,223 --> 00:30:46,057
No, not at... Not at all.

363
00:30:49,831 --> 00:30:53,358
It's just been a crazy couple of years.

364
00:30:57,472 --> 00:30:58,871
It's probably his helicopter.

365
00:30:59,040 --> 00:31:01,167
His daughter
is supposed to be arriving today.

366
00:31:01,342 --> 00:31:04,072
The whole town is buzzing
with excitement.

367
00:31:22,597 --> 00:31:26,431
Hey, so where you say
this, uh, museum is at?

368
00:31:28,102 --> 00:31:30,332
Number 2, Water Street.

369
00:31:30,505 --> 00:31:34,032
Okay, uh, every street on this island
is called Water Street.

370
00:31:34,208 --> 00:31:36,938
This place has a magic atmosphere.

371
00:31:37,111 --> 00:31:39,079
Will you just find
the damn address, man?

372
00:31:39,247 --> 00:31:41,772
Yo, Cordell, we got MapQuest
on these things?

373
00:32:23,958 --> 00:32:26,324
- Hi, Daddy.
- Hello, darling.

374
00:32:28,930 --> 00:32:30,830
Hello, my baby.

375
00:32:30,999 --> 00:32:32,694
Daddy.

376
00:32:38,106 --> 00:32:40,870
- Pleasant flight?
- Uh-huh.

377
00:32:41,943 --> 00:32:44,810
So, um, is this the whole boat?

378
00:32:46,547 --> 00:32:50,210
- Yes.
- Oh, so cute.

379
00:32:50,385 --> 00:32:52,717
I can't believe we're at sea.

380
00:32:52,887 --> 00:32:56,050
Well, uh, technically, we're at anchor.

381
00:32:56,224 --> 00:33:02,163
Oh, wait, okay. So that just means
that the anchor is in the water, right?

382
00:33:03,064 --> 00:33:04,361
- Yes.
- Yes.

383
00:33:04,532 --> 00:33:07,933
Okay. Because I totally wanna learn
all the sea terms.

384
00:33:08,102 --> 00:33:09,933
And so you shall, my darling.

385
00:33:10,104 --> 00:33:13,335
Okay, let me try again.
Excuse me, Nigel.

386
00:33:13,508 --> 00:33:15,874
Yes, my dear.

387
00:33:16,544 --> 00:33:18,603
You know what,
let's not do the accent thing.

388
00:33:18,813 --> 00:33:20,337
It's no good?

389
00:33:22,050 --> 00:33:23,813
It's fine.

390
00:33:24,085 --> 00:33:26,212
Um... Anyway...

391
00:33:26,387 --> 00:33:31,222
Nigel, remember when you asked me
this afternoon what I really did?

392
00:33:45,606 --> 00:33:46,903
Have fun shopping.

393
00:33:47,075 --> 00:33:48,702
Thank you, Daddy.

394
00:33:48,876 --> 00:33:51,344
Do try to keep it
under 50 thousand.

395
00:33:52,146 --> 00:33:53,170
What? Ha.

396
00:33:54,982 --> 00:33:56,176
Supper's at 7.

397
00:33:56,350 --> 00:34:00,047
I was supposed to meet some friends,
but I'm gonna try to get out of it.

398
00:34:00,221 --> 00:34:02,485
Invite them aboard if you like.
Just let me know.

399
00:34:02,657 --> 00:34:04,682
Okay, I will. Love you.

400
00:34:24,045 --> 00:34:25,376
My hat.

401
00:34:33,654 --> 00:34:36,555
Hey, look. The hat, he is a Frisbee.

402
00:34:36,724 --> 00:34:38,885
Can you turn the boat around?
Thank you.

403
00:34:39,060 --> 00:34:41,688
Okay, but we never gonna catch him.

404
00:35:05,987 --> 00:35:07,284
Whoa!

405
00:35:10,458 --> 00:35:11,482
God.

406
00:35:15,630 --> 00:35:17,097
- Oh, shit.
- Oh.

407
00:35:19,000 --> 00:35:22,128
Oh, my God. You killed him.

408
00:35:22,970 --> 00:35:25,165
Ow. Ow. Ow.

409
00:35:30,344 --> 00:35:31,971
What in God's name happened?

410
00:35:32,580 --> 00:35:35,606
Daddy, this man saved my life.

411
00:35:35,783 --> 00:35:37,444
Sir, sir...

412
00:35:37,885 --> 00:35:40,979
...I really don't think you should get up
until I make sure...

413
00:35:50,998 --> 00:35:53,159
Is this your hat?

414
00:35:53,835 --> 00:35:54,995
Yes. Ha-ha.

415
00:35:56,204 --> 00:36:01,801
That was the bravest thing
I've ever seen in my life.

416
00:36:03,311 --> 00:36:07,645
Sir, thank you so much.

417
00:36:07,815 --> 00:36:08,839
Thank you.

418
00:36:09,016 --> 00:36:10,711
- Thank you, indeed.
- He'll be okay.

419
00:36:10,885 --> 00:36:12,785
Just a little bump on the head.

420
00:36:12,954 --> 00:36:16,515
Just try not to move around too much
for the next few hours.

421
00:36:17,225 --> 00:36:21,355
- But I gotta go back to town.
- Oh, I really don't advise it.

422
00:36:21,729 --> 00:36:22,923
Oh...

423
00:36:23,164 --> 00:36:24,461
Now what am I gonna do?

424
00:36:25,333 --> 00:36:26,425
Uh...

425
00:36:26,601 --> 00:36:30,833
May I suggest a hot shower,
some clean clothes...

426
00:36:31,005 --> 00:36:32,302
...and cocktails at 6:30?

427
00:36:32,907 --> 00:36:36,070
Okay. Thanks.

428
00:36:37,345 --> 00:36:39,745
Take him to the Saint Regis.

429
00:36:41,515 --> 00:36:46,009
Whoa, whoa.
Yep, yep, yep, I'm good. I'm good.

430
00:36:47,355 --> 00:36:48,913
Hey, Mr. Honeycutt?

431
00:36:49,090 --> 00:36:52,753
Miss Honeycutt,
she leave him on the boat.

432
00:36:52,927 --> 00:36:56,556
Gemma. Your lifeline
to civilization, darling.

433
00:36:59,233 --> 00:37:00,791
Oh.

434
00:37:01,102 --> 00:37:04,003
Oh, my God, I would have been so dead.

435
00:37:04,171 --> 00:37:06,139
Here you are, darling.

436
00:37:13,814 --> 00:37:18,274
Well, Mr. Deenz, I'm always delighted
to welcome an entrant into my field...

437
00:37:18,452 --> 00:37:20,784
...whether it be on land or sea.

438
00:37:21,355 --> 00:37:24,119
But I feel I need to warn you.

439
00:37:24,425 --> 00:37:26,552
There's no way
of getting away from treasure...

440
00:37:26,727 --> 00:37:29,389
...once it's fastened itself on your mind.

441
00:37:29,563 --> 00:37:32,054
I want you to find me the Queen's Dowry.

442
00:37:32,233 --> 00:37:33,564
Heh.

443
00:37:33,734 --> 00:37:37,602
- Well, now, Bunny, uh...
- Bigg Bunny. It's one word.

444
00:37:40,107 --> 00:37:42,735
Well, that's an emerald
of a different color, isn't it?

445
00:37:43,411 --> 00:37:45,038
Cordell.

446
00:37:51,786 --> 00:37:55,517
This is a piece of the plate
that we found in the Bahamas...

447
00:37:55,690 --> 00:37:59,490
...off of Topsail Cay.
Now, if you turn it over...

448
00:37:59,660 --> 00:38:03,118
...you may notice that it has
the Vangor family crest stamped on it.

449
00:38:03,297 --> 00:38:05,231
That's what that is right there.

450
00:38:06,968 --> 00:38:08,230
That's very nice, uh...

451
00:38:10,171 --> 00:38:12,264
...but who the hell are the Vangors...

452
00:38:12,440 --> 00:38:16,274
...and why the hell should I give
a rat's ass about their family crest?

453
00:38:21,349 --> 00:38:25,115
It's not an investment, per se,
because you probably won't see a dime...

454
00:38:25,286 --> 00:38:28,084
...but it's a chance to pull out
a piece of living history...

455
00:38:28,255 --> 00:38:31,088
...from the sand
with your own two hands.

456
00:38:34,362 --> 00:38:35,522
<i>To the Aurelia.</i>

457
00:38:39,000 --> 00:38:40,467
Hey, babe.

458
00:38:41,168 --> 00:38:42,396
What are you doing here?

459
00:38:42,570 --> 00:38:44,162
Have a good dinner.

460
00:38:45,706 --> 00:38:47,765
<i>Bon appétit, everybody.</i>

461
00:38:48,976 --> 00:38:50,000
Ugh!

462
00:38:54,715 --> 00:38:56,444
I take it you've met.

463
00:38:56,917 --> 00:39:02,048
So Tess and I first hooked up when
we worked for this cat named Moe Fitch.

464
00:39:02,223 --> 00:39:05,989
He's kind of a local character, you know,
big talker, lot of tall tales...

465
00:39:06,160 --> 00:39:07,559
...a lovable, old sea dog.

466
00:39:07,728 --> 00:39:11,391
- You should live to be so eccentric.
- Ooh...

467
00:39:11,565 --> 00:39:12,964
Thank you, babe.

468
00:39:13,134 --> 00:39:15,034
I do wish you would sit down.

469
00:39:15,636 --> 00:39:19,299
Moe Fitch is the most respected and
successful treasure salvor in the world.

470
00:39:19,473 --> 00:39:21,532
- Nobody said he wasn't.
- When Finn met Moe...

471
00:39:21,709 --> 00:39:23,904
...he was repairing outboards
and lawn mowers...

472
00:39:24,078 --> 00:39:26,546
...during the brief intervals
he wasn't getting fired.

473
00:39:26,714 --> 00:39:28,614
Two times, Tess. I got fired two times.

474
00:39:28,783 --> 00:39:30,648
I'll be off in one second.

475
00:39:31,085 --> 00:39:34,020
Moe picked him out of a puddle
of motor oil and suntan lotion...

476
00:39:34,188 --> 00:39:38,420
...gave him a job, a vocation,
taught him everything he knows.

477
00:39:40,594 --> 00:39:42,289
Almost.

478
00:39:43,798 --> 00:39:47,234
Anyway, then they had a tremendous
falling-out over this cannon we found...

479
00:39:47,401 --> 00:39:49,164
On our day off.

480
00:39:49,336 --> 00:39:52,430
<i>From the Aurelia,
three miles east of Vero Beach.</i>

481
00:39:52,606 --> 00:39:56,133
Which the court ruled was Moe's,
because we borrowed his equipment.

482
00:39:57,912 --> 00:40:00,380
The sea is all attached, right?

483
00:40:00,714 --> 00:40:02,545
To what, darling?

484
00:40:02,716 --> 00:40:05,276
Kerry and Vivante
grabbed a plane for the Yucatân...

485
00:40:05,453 --> 00:40:07,683
...and I thought
we could hook up with them...

486
00:40:07,855 --> 00:40:10,722
...instead of just sailing around
doing nothing.

487
00:40:12,827 --> 00:40:14,761
Tell us about the treasure.

488
00:40:21,202 --> 00:40:24,694
July 31 st, 1715.

489
00:40:24,872 --> 00:40:28,638
A hurricane sinks the entire Spanish
treasure fleet off the coast of Florida...

490
00:40:28,809 --> 00:40:31,300
<i>...including her flagship, the Capitana...</i>

491
00:40:31,479 --> 00:40:35,575
...which, according to its manifest,
carried the Queen's Dowry.

492
00:40:35,749 --> 00:40:39,116
Forty chests
of jewelry and gold crowns...

493
00:40:39,286 --> 00:40:42,312
...especially crafted in the Orient
for the new queen of Spain.

494
00:40:42,490 --> 00:40:44,958
When we say jewels, we mean...

495
00:40:45,126 --> 00:40:51,031
...Indian diamonds, Burmese rubies and
Colombian emeralds the size of your fist.

496
00:40:51,198 --> 00:40:55,032
We should probably start with what Tess
and I got excited about on our honeymoon.

497
00:40:55,202 --> 00:40:57,261
Well, I think we can all guess.

498
00:40:59,273 --> 00:41:01,298
After we lost the court case...

499
00:41:01,475 --> 00:41:04,205
...we decided to go backpacking in Spain
for two weeks.

500
00:41:05,146 --> 00:41:09,276
Ended up spending two years
in the Archives of the Indies in Seville.

501
